 a target for bullying; &#10;- spend more time teaching than on &quot;crowd control&quot; in classrooms;&#10;then parents will keep choosing to take their children out of the public system if they think their children will suffer in the lowest-common-denominator culture that is prevalent in many schools. (Principals and teachers in public schools may think otherwise about their schools, but it's the attitude of peers that matters the most in the junior years of high school.) "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="761" language="en" documentId="4526" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Tim" date="September 04, 2013, 10:34AM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.theage.com.au/comment/private-schools-and-the-art-of-ripping-off-parents-20130903-2t357.html" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4526" notes="" title="Private schools and the art of ripping off parents"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="122"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="123" end="220"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="221" end="323"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="324" end="389"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="390" end="761"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>